class Solution {
    public int longestDecomposition(String text) {
        int n = text.length();
        int left = 0, right = n - 1;
        int count = 0;
        String prefix = "", suffix = "";
        while (left <= right) {
            prefix += text.charAt(left);
            suffix = text.charAt(right) + suffix;
            if (prefix.equals(suffix)) {
                count += 2;
                prefix = "";
                suffix = "";
            }
            left++;
            right--;
        }
        if (!prefix.isEmpty()) count--;
        return count;
    }
}
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(N)
space complexity: O(N)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The solution uses a two-pointer approach, comparing characters from the start and end of the string, and counting the number of matching substrings from both ends. It handles the case where the string length is odd by decrementing the count if there's a remaining substring in the middle.
